@john ezra
As for THAT-AWAY: nothing bothersome for Italians in that clue. The 'extra' A in the answer is just the Western/rural US habit of inserting an A before directional words: afore, arear, alee, away. It is a preserved remnant of even older forms of speech from Great Britain.
It is entirely unconnected with the parodic Ital-ish in which all final plosives (and occasionally other final consonants or even vowels!) elicit an added schwa. Good-a, bad-a, stop-a, went-a, you-a, etc. This is not THAT-A WAY but THAT A-WAY.

